A useful design principle for the Pantheon is to favor words that are generative rather than merely descriptive. For example, “Reconstruct” implies a repeatable process, “Invariant” points to something testable across contexts, “Range” suggests estimation toward a target, and “Cultivate” frames knowledge as something that grows over time. A compact vocabulary of these kinds of terms can serve as semantic primitives from which more specialized doctrines, operators, and architectures are built.